A river. It rises south of La Marque in central Galveston County and runs southeast for more than twelve miles before passing into Jones Bay and West Bay.

A river that originates south of Lubbock, Texas on the Llano Estacado, near Lamesa, Texas. It flows generally southeast, out of the Llano Estacado and through the Texas Hill Country, through several reservoirs including Lake J.B. Thomas, E.V. Spence Reservoir, and Lake O.H. Ivie. The river flows through several more reservoirs before reaching Austin, including Lake Buchanan, Lake Lyndon B. Johnson, and Lake Travis. The Llano River joins the Colorado south of Lake Buchanan. After passing through Austin the Colorado River continues flowing southeast until discharging to Matagorda Bay on the Gulf of Mexico, near Matagorda.

A river. It rises on the western city limits of El Campo, twelve miles southwest of Wharton in central Wharton County and runs southeast for forty-six miles, through the Eldorado Country, Tidewater Oaks, and Tres Palacios developments, to its mouth on Tres Palacios Bay, four miles north of Palacios in southwestern Matagorda County.
A river.
Spelling? Carancahua Creek?

A river. It rises a mile northwest of the Victoria county line in extreme southeastern DeWitt County and flows southeast for 48 miles to its mouth on Garcitas Cove, off Lavaca Bay. It forms a major drainage system in Victoria County and constitutes the Victoria-Jackson county line in its last twelve miles.

A river in Texas. It is formed by the confluence of Blanco and Medio creeks in central Refugio County and runs southeast, past Refugio, for twenty-four miles to its mouth on Mission Bay, an inlet of Copano Bay.

A river in south Texas in the United States. It drains an area of the south Texas coastal plains into the Gulf of Mexico at Copano Bay. It rises in Bee County southwest of Beeville and north of Skidmore, from the confluence of three creeks: Olmos, Aransas, and Poesta.

A river. It is formed by the confluence of Agua Dulce and Banquete creeks, a mile southeast of Banquete in western Nueces County. It runs southeast for forty-four miles to its mouth on Cayo del Mazon, sixteen miles northeast of Riviera Beach in eastern Kleberg County.

A river. It is formed by the confluence of Chiltipin and San Diego creeks one mile northeast of Alice in central Jim Wells County and runs southeast for forty-four miles, forming the Kleberg-Nueces county line, to its mouth on Cayo del Grullo, seven miles southeast of Kingsville in east central Kleberg County.

A river. It is formed by the confluence of Agua Poquita and Concepcion creeks eight miles south of Benavides in southern Duval County and runs southeast for seventy-one miles. It traverses Jim Wells and Brooks counties, forms the line between Kleberg and Kenedy counties, and discharges to Laguna Salado, an inlet of Baffin Bay.

A river. Located in the Rio Grande delta, originates at Lake Llano Grande in Hidalgo County and flows northeast for fifty-two miles through Cameron and southeastern Willacy counties to its mouth opposite Padre Island on Laguna Madre .

A river in northwestern Ohio and northeastern Indiana in the United States. It is formed at Fort Wayne, Indiana by the confluence of the Saint Joseph and Saint Marys rivers, and meanders northeastwardly for about 209 km through an agricultural region of glacial moraines before flowing into the Maumee Bay of Lake Erie at the city of Toledo, Ohio.

A river that flows through Little River, South Carolina, briefly touching the border with North Carolina before discharging to the Atlantic Ocean.

A river in South Carolina in the United States. It is formed in central South Carolina 40 km southeast of Columbia by the confluence of the Wateree and Congaree rivers. It flows southeast for 8 km before entering the northwest corner of Lake Marion. Downstream from the reservoir it flows east, then southeast, forming the northeast boundary of Francis Marion National Forest. Approximately 16 km from its mouth it bifurcates into two channels, called the North Santee and South Santee, that flow parallel and separated by approximately 3 km, creating Cedar Island. The two channels reach the ocean at Santee Point, approximately 24 km south of Georgetown, and not far from the mouth of the Pee Dee River.

A river. A tributary of the Broad River. Formed by the confluence of the North Pacolet River and South Pacolet River. They join 16 km north-northeast of Spartanburg, and the Pacolet then flows generally southeastwardly, through or along the boundaries of Spartanburg, Cherokee and Union Counties, through Lake Blalock and past the town of Central Pacolet. It joins the Broad River on the common boundary of Cherokee and Union Counties, 6 km north of the town of Lockhart.

A tidal channel in Southeast South Carolina, Southwest of Charleston. The channel runs Southwest to Northeast between mainland (NW) and Wadmalaw Island and Johns Island (SE), from North Edisto River through between Johns (West) and James (East) Island. The Intracoastal Waterway runs through Southwest-Northeast section of the channel.
A river.

A short blackwater river in South Carolina. It rises in a confluence of swamps south of Walterboro, flows in southeast direction and then empties into Saint Helena Sound. The entire course of the river lies within the boundaries of Colleton County.

A short blackwater river in the Southern Lowcountry region of South Carolina formed at the confluence of the Salkehatchie and Little Salkehatchie rivers near the Islandton community of Colleton County, South Carolina.
A river.
A tidal river.
A tidal river.

A tidal channel, in Beaufort and Jasper County, South Carolina. The channel flows between mainland on the west and Port Royal and Parris Islands on the east. The Coosawhatchie River flows into the Broad River at the head. It joins Coosaw River channel Northeast and continues Southeast to Atlantic Ocean as Port Royal Sound.

A coastal water-body in Northeastern North Carolina in the United States. Located between Camden and Pasquotank counties, the Pasquotank connects directly to the Albemarle Sound and is part of the Intracoastal Waterway via Elizabeth City.
A blackwater river formed with the merging of Virginia's Blackwater and Nottoway rivers near the stateline between Virginia and North Carolina. Drains into Albemarle Sound.
A blackwater river that flows through Tyrrell County and Washington County into the Albemarle Sound of North Carolina in the United States.

A small river in eastern North Carolina, USA, separating Dare County with Tyrrell County. It is a tributary of the Albemarle Sound and is part of the Alligator River National Wildlife Refuge. A 21-mile canal connects the Alligator River with the Pungo River to its west.
A tidal river.
A tidal river.
A river rising in the piedmont of North Carolina, discharging to the Pamlico Sound below New Bern.

A tidal river, approximately 29 km long, in eastern North Carolina, the United States. It forms the boundary between Currituck and Camden counties. The river rises in the Great Swamp, 10 miles east of Elizabeth City, North Carolina at the juncture of Indiantown Creek. The river's mouth, where it is approximately four miles wide, is in Albemarle Sound, midway between the mouth of the Pasquotank River to the west and the south end of Currituck Sound to the east. The lower two-thirds of the river is part of the Intracoastal Waterway.
A small river in North Carolina that runs approximately twenty km southeast through the town of Newport with its mouth opening into Bogue Sound, between Morehead City and Beaufort.

A blackwater tiver that rises in the White Oak Pocosin in northern Onslow County approximately 24 km north of Jacksonville. It flows east, then SSE, along the border between Onslow, Jones and Carteret counties, and forming the western boundary of Croatan National Forest. The lower 16 km of the river is a tidal estuary, approximately 1.6 km wide. It enters the Atlantic at Bogue Sound, then passes between two barrier islands (Bogue Banks and Bear Island) through Bogue Inlet into the open Atlantic at Onslow Bay.

A river in southeastern North Carolina in the United States. It empties into the Atlantic Ocean. It rises in northwestern Onslow County and flows east-southeast past Jacksonville, where it widens into a tidal estuary approximately 3.2 km wide. As an estuary it meanders through Marine Corps Base Camp Lejeune and enters the Atlantic in Onslow Bay, via the New River Inlet between two barrier islands.
